## Layer 4: System Execution Order — The Full Picture
```
SimulationSystemGroup (each frame, in order):
│
├── SpawnerSystem          → Instantiates enemy prefabs, sets MoveTarget
├── EnemyMovementSystem    → Moves all enemies toward Command Building (parallel job)
├── TargetingSystem        → Writes TargetComponent on each turret base
├── TurretRotationSystem   → Reads TargetComponent, rotates mount (parallel job)
├── TurretFireSystem       → (you build next) Reads TargetComponent, fires projectiles
└── HealthSystem           → Destroys dead entities via ECB

The [UpdateAfter] attributes enforce this order without a brittle central coordinator.

Layer 5: Extensibility — How to Add Features Without Rewrites
Feature                     What you add                                        What you touch      
Energy Consumption          EnergyConsumerComponent, EnergyGridSystem           Nothing — just query turrets that 
                                                                                have the new component

Pathfinding around walls    PathfindingComponent + waypoint DynamicBufferOnly   MoveTargetComponent.Value lookup 
                                                                                in EnemyMovementSystem

Enemy types (fast, armored) New tag (ArmoredEnemyTag) + override components     Add a filter in TargetingSystem to 
                                                                                prioritize armored targets

Turret upgrades             TurretTierComponent + upgrade system                TurretWeaponComponent.Damage/Range 
                                                                                are already data-driven

Spatial partitioning        Replace inner loop in TargetingSystem               Only TargetingSystem internals — 
                                                                                TargetComponent interface unchanged

Area damage                 SplashDamageComponent on projectile prefabNew       SplashDamageSystem — zero changes to 
                                                                                turret or enemy systems

Key Architecture Principles at Work
    1.  Components are nouns, Systems are verbs. HealthComponent holds data. 
        HealthSystem acts on it. They never cross.
    2.  [UpdateAfter] instead of Update() ordering. Unity guarantees the dependency graph — 
        you never fight frame-order bugs.
    3.  EntityCommandBuffer for all structural changes. You never add/remove components or 
        destroy entities inside a job. ECBs batch those operations safely.
    4.  ComponentLookup for cross-entity reads. When a Mount needs to know its Base's target, 
        it doesn't iterate — it does an O(1) lookup by entity handle.
    5.  Prefab-based spawning. Instantiate(prefab) in ECS copies all baked components atomically. 
        No manual component assignment at runtime.


This gives you a foundation where adding a 6th system doesn't break the first five, and profiling one system doesn't require understanding all others.